        "timestamp": 1638305633
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"306601\">@Kyle Miller</span> I think another thing you can do for the Grassmannian is to define it as the quotient of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><mtext>rank-</mtext><mi>k</mi><mtext> endomorphisms of </mtext><mi>V</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\{\\text{rank-}k\\text{ endomorphisms of }V\\}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">{</span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">rank-</span></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\"> endomorphisms of </span></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span><span class=\"mclose\">}</span></span></span></span> by <del>the conjugation action of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi><mi>L</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>V</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">GL(V)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span></del> edit : I don't think I mean that, the quotient by something else :).</p>",
        "id": 263207467,
        "sender_full_name": "Heather Macbeth",
        "timestamp": 1638305874
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>... maybe just the quotient by the left-multiplication action, since that ought to preserve the kernel.</p>",
        "id": 263208031,
        "sender_full_name": "Heather Macbeth",
        "timestamp": 1638306072
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"260507\">Heather Macbeth</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/113489-new-members/topic/Smooth.20varieties.20are.20smooth.20manifolds/near/263206968\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"267205\">Nicolò Cavalleri</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/113489-new-members/topic/Smooth.20varieties.20are.20smooth.20manifolds/near/263195884\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"260507\">Heather Macbeth</span> How about the regular value theorem? I guess that could be a first step for the original project anyways</p>\n<p>But without the submanifold part, just to prove that the preimage of a regular value is a manifold</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>That seems reasonable to me, but I'd check with <span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"110050\">Sebastien Gouezel</span> and <span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"110031\">Patrick Massot</span> too.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>For some reason I was convinced you wanted to work on this before... Am I getting confused? If not what stopped you if anything did?</p>",
        "id": 263212585,
        "sender_full_name": "Nicolò Cavalleri",
        "timestamp": 1638308355
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I started trying to define pullbacks of groupoids, morphisms of groupoids, etc, and got really confused :)<br>\n<a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib/compare/submanifolds-1\">https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib/compare/submanifolds-1</a></p>",
        "id": 263212843,
        "sender_full_name": "Heather Macbeth",
        "timestamp": 1638308505
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I would like to return to it at some point, or see someone else do it, but I think it needs a very clear head.</p>",
        "id": 263212937,
        "sender_full_name": "Heather Macbeth",
        "timestamp": 1638308540
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But this is for the submanifolds part right? If one only cares about the manifold structure things are much easier I guess</p>",
        "id": 263213605,
        "sender_full_name": "Nicolò Cavalleri",
        "timestamp": 1638308922
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I  think it's very important to prove that the preimage of a regular value is a manifold. We can't really claim we have a differential geometry library without this result. But it would be even nicer to do it more generally for the preimage of a submanifold under a map which is transverse to the submanifold.</p>",
        "id": 263213677,
        "sender_full_name": "Patrick Massot",
        "timestamp": 1638308959
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If you want to state this more general version then you'll need submanifolds anyway.</p>",
        "id": 263213711,
        "sender_full_name": "Patrick Massot",
        "timestamp": 1638308988
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The case of preimages of a point is easier only because by accident it's easier to prove that a point is a submanifold...</p>",
        "id": 263213790,
        "sender_full_name": "Patrick Massot",
        "timestamp": 1638309019
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"267205\">@Nicolò Cavalleri</span> ?? You're on the LSGNT now?? Come to Xena on Thursdays at Imperial! Did you meet Amelia and Jujian? They're in your cohort and both Lean experts!</p>",
        "id": 263214502,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1638309417
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Jujian is working on GAGA for his thesis.</p>",
        "id": 263214534,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1638309435
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"110038\">@Kevin Buzzard</span> which part??</p>",
        "id": 263214616,
        "sender_full_name": "Heather Macbeth",
        "timestamp": 1638309476
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I am in charge of admissions so I should have known you were in London, but I was on sabbatical last year and played no part in the admissions process. I've only just noticed you're on the list of newcomers!</p>",
        "id": 263214693,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1638309504
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"260507\">@Heather Macbeth</span> right now Jujian is defining projective varieties and learning the material. I don't know whether it's ridiculously optimistic to do GAGA but I thought we could give it a try, we have 4 years.</p>",
        "id": 263214780,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1638309569
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Back to submanifolds: I'd like to know that a regular level set, equipped with the smooth manifold structure Nicolo is talking about, has inclusion function which is an immersion and a topological embedding.  And in the other direction, to know that a topological embedding which is a smooth immersion has image which is locally the level set of of some submersion.</p>",
        "id": 263214962,
        "sender_full_name": "Heather Macbeth",
        "timestamp": 1638309626
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Nico who are the others interested in Lean who you mentioned above? Mel, Amelia, David, Sebastian and Jujian are all doing Lean mini-projects with me this year.</p>",
        "id": 263215054,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1638309679
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Back to submanifolds: do we have the implicit function theorem?</p>",
        "id": 263215107,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1638309711
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yup, thanks to Yury 18 months ago.</p>",
        "id": 263215152,
        "sender_full_name": "Heather Macbeth",
        "timestamp": 1638309724
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So is the submanifold thing a whole lot more difficult?</p>",
        "id": 263215212,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1638309752
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(Back to GAGA: maybe Chow's theorem, that an analytic subvariety of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">P</mi></mrow><mi>n</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{CP}^n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7432em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">CP</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7432em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.1418em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is an algebraic subvariety?  This doesn't require too much sheaf-y machinery.)</p>",
        "id": 263215396,
        "sender_full_name": "Heather Macbeth",
        "timestamp": 1638309845
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Right now Jujian is tempted to start thinking about cohomology theories. I wonder if I should just PR group cohomology, I have it sitting on a branch. We still don't have any cohomology theories other than <code>derived_functor</code> (for which I still don't think we have the long exact sequence!). I thought that the proof of Chow's theorem involved showing that the analytic sheaf corresponding to the zero locus of the analytic subvariety was algebraic?</p>",
        "id": 263215586,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1638309952
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Indeed, it seems I was thinking of an easier theorem (which I suppose is also a form of GAGA): the space of holomorphic sections of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">O</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>d</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{O}(d)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">O</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">d</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">P</mi></mrow><mi>n</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{CP}^n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7432em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">CP</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7432em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.1418em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is isomorphic to the space of degree-<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">d</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">d</span></span></span></span> polynomials in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n+1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span> variables.</p>",
        "id": 263216904,
        "sender_full_name": "Heather Macbeth",
        "timestamp": 1638310616
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah I think this is the initial target. In the algebraic category I think it's pretty easy. In the analytic category it will be more of a challenge.</p>",
        "id": 263216977,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1638310665
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I was really excited to see someone <a href=\"#narrow/stream/217875-Is-there.20code.20for.20X.3F/topic/Hartog's.20theorem\">talking about Hartogs's theorem</a> the other day, but it turned out to be the wrong Hartogs's theorem :)</p>",
        "id": 263217183,
        "sender_full_name": "Heather Macbeth",
        "timestamp": 1638310793
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Heh, I once had the same experience in a conversation with Nick Katz!</p>",
        "id": 263217256,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1638310818
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"110038\">Kevin Buzzard</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/113489-new-members/topic/Smooth.20varieties.20are.20smooth.20manifolds/near/263214502\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"267205\">Nicolò Cavalleri</span> ?? You're on the LSGNT now?? Come to Xena on Thursdays at Imperial! Did you meet Amelia and Jujian? They're in your cohort and both Lean experts!</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Yes!! Amelia told me but I did not speak with Jujian about Lean yet! I think I crossed you at Imperial but you were in a rush and I did not want to stop you!</p>",
        "id": 263217696,
        "sender_full_name": "Nicolò Cavalleri",
        "timestamp": 1638311072
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"110038\">Kevin Buzzard</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/113489-new-members/topic/Smooth.20varieties.20are.20smooth.20manifolds/near/263215054\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Nico who are the others interested in Lean who you mentioned above? Mel, Amelia, David, Sebastian and Jujian are all doing Lean mini-projects with me this year.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>One is <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"460212\">@Sebastian Monnet</span> and the other is Michela who is not on this chat yet!</p>",
        "id": 263217891,
        "sender_full_name": "Nicolò Cavalleri",
        "timestamp": 1638311170
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah, seems like a great opportunity to learn some Lean in preparation for the project</p>",
        "id": 263218621,
        "sender_full_name": "Sebastian Monnet",
        "timestamp": 1638311575
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"267205\">@Nicolò Cavalleri</span> Another project would be to define complex (analytic) spaces and then prove that both schemes over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">C</span></span></span></span> and complex manifolds are special cases.</p>",
        "id": 263219397,
        "sender_full_name": "Heather Macbeth",
        "timestamp": 1638311994
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This would be an excellent project. I guess the schemes over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">C</span></span></span></span> would need some finiteness assumptions. <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"252627\">@Jujian Zhang</span> do you know Nico? He's on the LSGNT.</p>",
        "id": 263219528,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1638312060
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Is the preimage theorem even true for manifolds with corners? If yes I believe we have a problem with the current implementation of model with corners cause to do things naturally in the proof at some point you'd need to show that the intersection of a subspace with a model with corners is again a model with corners and this is not true with the current implementation. <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"110050\">@Sebastien Gouezel</span></p>",
        "id": 263943215,
        "sender_full_name": "Nicolò Cavalleri",
        "timestamp": 1638836055
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Most naive statements are not true for manifolds with boundary. The basic example to keep in mind is the following. Consider the graph <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">M</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span></span></span> of the function <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>↦</mo><msup><mi>e</mi><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></msup><mi>sin</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x \\mapsto e^{-1/x^2} \\sin (1/x)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.522em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↦</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.2369em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.9869em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">−</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">1/</span><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">x</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8913em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.931em;margin-right:0.0714em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.5em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size3 size1 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\">sin</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">1/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>. It is a smooth submanifold of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\R^2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>. Now consider the inclusion <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>i</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">i</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6595em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">i</span></span></span></span> of the upper half plane (with boundary) into <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\R^2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>. Then its differential is everywhere invertible, but still <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>i</mi><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>M</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">i^{-1}(M)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0641em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">i</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">−</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> is extremely nasty around <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span></span></span></span> (it has infinitely many connected components, for instance).</p>",
        "id": 263970055,
        "sender_full_name": "Sebastien Gouezel",
        "timestamp": 1638865285
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ok thanks although I believe this can be a counterexample for the preimage of a manifold. As for the preimage of a point I believe that if the regular value is not on the boundary then the theorem holds for manifolds with boundary. However I am not sure if this extends to corners: I expect it does but the proof I had in mind requires that the intersection of a subspace with a model with corners is still a model with corners and this is not true with the current implementation</p>",
        "id": 263991271,
        "sender_full_name": "Nicolò Cavalleri",
        "timestamp": 1638878676
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Would you suggest just proving the theorem in the boundaryless case?</p>",
        "id": 263991333,
        "sender_full_name": "Nicolò Cavalleri",
        "timestamp": 1638878719
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, I'd just state and prove this in the boundaryless case.</p>",
        "id": 263994290,
        "sender_full_name": "Sebastien Gouezel",
        "timestamp": 1638880678
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ok this is what we partially did in the end but this project made wonder: what are the advantages of having model with corners so general? I propose imposing some constraint on them such that they are closed under the operation of restricting them to a subspace, so that a theorem like this ones can be proved in such context. Something like adding a condition that 0 must be in the interior of the target?</p>",
        "id": 264210716,
        "sender_full_name": "Nicolò Cavalleri",
        "timestamp": 1638993190
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"267205\">Nicolò Cavalleri</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/113489-new-members/topic/Smooth.20varieties.20are.20smooth.20manifolds/near/263991271\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Ok thanks although I believe this can be a counterexample for the preimage of a manifold. As for the preimage of a point I believe that if the regular value is not on the boundary then the theorem holds for manifolds with boundary. However I am not sure if this extends to corners: I expect it does but the proof I had in mind requires that the intersection of a subspace with a model with corners is still a model with corners and this is not true with the current implementation</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>By the way, this does extend to corners because apparently it is true for orbifolds...</p>",
        "id": 264244423,
        "sender_full_name": "Nicolò Cavalleri",
        "timestamp": 1639012408
    }
]